      <section id="progress" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Progress on the cross-modality pipeline — what has actually been built</h2>
        <p>
          The pipeline figure earlier on this page draws an <em>aspirational</em>
          cross-modality system, assembled from the QuIC reference architecture in
          Awschalom et&nbsp;al. (PRX Quantum 2021) <SourceNote
          id="awschalom-prxquantum-2021" />. The honest position as of 2026: no single
          published experiment runs the whole thing — transmon compute + M-O
          transducer + matter memory + QFC + fibre + heralded entanglement +
          mirrored stack at the far end — end-to-end. The closest experiments close
          either some of the boxes, or all of the boxes but at lower stakes than
          full entanglement distribution between two computers.
        </p>

        <h3>The full memory + entanglement chain — Knaut <em>et&nbsp;al.</em>, Nature 629, 573 (2024)</h3>
        <p>
          The cleanest demonstration of the <strong>memory + heralded entanglement
          + telecom-fibre</strong> half of the picture. Two SiV-in-diamond nodes
          sit in Cambridge and Boston laboratories, connected by 35&nbsp;km of
          deployed telecom fibre at 1350&nbsp;nm (PPLN QFC from the SiV's native
          737&nbsp;nm). Each node uses one SiV centre as both comm qubit and memory
          (see <a href={url("/repeaters#node-architecture")}>repeaters § node
          architecture</a>). The protocol runs end-to-end: each node emits a
          matter-photon entangled pair, the photons fly to a midpoint photonic BSM,
          the herald fires, the two nodes are left with comm-A ↔ comm-B Bell-paired,
          and the entanglement is mapped into the nuclear-spin memory for storage.
          QFC ran at 33% (DFG) / 30% (SFG), the heralded entanglement fidelity stayed
          above the classical bound after fibre transit, and the nuclear-spin memory
          held the state for the herald round-trip. The catch is that the link is
          <strong>same-modality</strong> end-to-end, so there is no transmon and no
          M-O transducer in the picture — the compute–network QuIC collapses onto
          operations inside the SiV itself <SourceNote id="knaut-nature-2024" />.
        </p>

        <h3>Closing the M-O transducer box on a real transmon — Warner <em>et&nbsp;al.</em>, Nature Physics 21, 831 (2025)</h3>
        <p>
          The first <strong>compute–network QuIC operating at single-photon level
          on a superconducting transmon</strong>. The Lončar group at Harvard,
          with Rigetti supplying the qubit, used a thin-film lithium-niobate
          electro-optic transducer to drive a transmon coherently with optical
          pulses — optically-driven Rabi oscillations on a real superconducting
          qubit without measurable degradation of its coherence time. Conversion
          efficiency up to 1.18%. Single node, no fibre between two QCs, no
          entanglement, but this closes the M-O-transducer box on a real
          transmon and shows that the compute–network QuIC is becoming
          experimentally viable on the superconducting platform
          <SourceNote id="warner-natphys-2025" />.
        </p>

        <h3>Coherent (not yet quantum) link between two fridges — Zhou &amp; Tang <em>et&nbsp;al.</em>, Nature Photonics 20, 579 (2026)</h3>
        <p>
          A <strong>1-km photonic link between two superconducting fridges</strong>,
          but only at coherent-classical level. Two AlN electro-optic transducers
          ("Felix" and "Albert") sit in two separate dilution refrigerators at
          Yale, each up- and down-converting between ~5&nbsp;GHz microwave and
          1573&nbsp;nm telecom optical, joined by a 1&nbsp;km fibre. Reported
          on-chip transduction efficiency &gt;0.1% per node, end-to-end link
          transmission &minus;60&nbsp;dB. For comparison, 1&nbsp;km of coaxial
          cable at 5&nbsp;GHz would lose ~1000&nbsp;dB; commercial electro-optic
          modulators would lose &minus;140&nbsp;dB. <strong>No memory in the
          picture, no entanglement</strong>: signals transferred this way are
          classical coherent waveforms, not heralded Bell pairs. To distribute
          entanglement, transducer efficiency has to climb from ~0.1% into the
          percent-to-tens-of-percent range <em>with sub-photon added noise</em>,
          and a memory has to be added at each node so the herald can be waited
          out <SourceNote id="zhou-natphoton-2026" />.
        </p>

        <Callout label="What still hasn't been demonstrated">
          <p>
            The experiment that would close the loop has not been published as of
            early 2026: transmon-A → M-O transducer → matter memory at A → QFC →
            telecom fibre → midpoint photonic BSM → mirrored stack at B →
            transmon-B, with the resulting heralded entanglement actually consumed
            by a remote two-qubit gate between the two superconducting computers.
            Knaut has the back half (memory + heralded entanglement over fibre);
            Warner has the front half on a real transmon (M-O transducer at
            single-photon level); Zhou–Tang has the geometry (two fridges, 1&nbsp;km
            link) but at classical-coherent power, with no memory and no
            heralding. Putting them together is the open problem.
          </p>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="encodings" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Encoding translation between photonic encodings</h2>
        <p>
          A separate flavour of conversion sits inside the optical band: translating
          between the photonic encodings different parts of the network use. The qubit-page
          encoding zoo — polarisation, time-bin, dual-rail (path), frequency-bin, Fock,
          coherent-state — names the choices; networking those choices means converting
          between them when subsystems disagree <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Polarisation ↔ time-bin.</strong> A polarising beam splitter plus a
            delay line maps the two polarisation modes onto two time-bin modes (or the
            reverse). Used when the source emits polarisation-encoded photons but the link
            is a deployed fibre that scrambles polarisation, in which case time-bin is the
            transmission encoding of choice — Caltech's 2024 time-bin teleportation at
            1536.5 nm is one example of operating directly in the time-bin
            encoding <SourceNote id="ezratty-uqt-2025-p4" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Time-bin ↔ dual-rail (path).</strong> An unbalanced interferometer
            converts the two time-bin modes into the two output ports of a beam splitter,
            and vice versa. Used at receiver nodes where a Bell-state measurement or a
            cavity interaction wants spatial-mode inputs.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Polarisation ↔ dual-rail (path).</strong> A polarising beam splitter
            does the conversion in one element. Used routinely inside linear-optics Bell
            measurement assemblies that combine photons from polarisation-encoded sources.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          These translations are linear-optics operations on a single photon — they are
          not quantum frequency conversion and they do not span the microwave-to-optical
          gap. They sit alongside QFC and M-O transduction as the third axis of
          "make the photon match the next subsystem" the link layer has to handle.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="q1-stack" data-nav-section>
        <h2>End-to-end Q1: heterogeneous endpoints in one figure</h2>
        <p>
          The cross-modality figure earlier on this page shows the transducer story
          in isolation. To answer Question&nbsp;1 — <em>what's required, top-down,
          to move a photon between two quantum computers</em> — the full system
          needs to be visible at once: surface-code QEC at each endpoint, the role
          decomposition into <em>data&nbsp;·&nbsp;memory&nbsp;·&nbsp;comm</em>
          qubits, the appropriate transducer on each side, the fibre with classical
          and sync co-channels, and the photonic Bell-state measurement at the
          meeting point. The figure below deliberately picks a <em>heterogeneous</em>
          pair to make the point: Node&nbsp;A is a superconducting transmon QC,
          Node&nbsp;B is a Diamond-SiV nanophotonic QC. The asymmetry inside the
          two node frames is the heterogeneity.
        </p>
        <figure class="demo-card q1-stack-figure">
          <img src={url("/images/q1-stack.svg")}
               alt="A seven-layer vertical stack diagram with two endpoint columns. Top: title and column headers — Node A (superconducting transmon, microwave-native) on the left, Node B (Diamond-SiV, visible-native) on the right, with a shared network/control plane between them. Each horizontal band is one layer of the stack, labelled on the far left. L7 Application: orange ψ data qubits at A and B with a 'share / teleport |ψ⟩' arrow between them. L6 Logical/QEC: small surface-code patches (4×4 grids) at each endpoint, with a middle note that EC lives at the endpoints, not the channel. L5 Network service: a wide pink box spanning A to B labelled '|Φ⁺⟩_AB delivered on request', with a magenta wavy entanglement line, and an RFC 9340 note. L4 Distillation: three small raw Bell pairs above one larger high-fidelity pair at each endpoint, with a 'trade rate for fidelity' arrow across the middle. L3 Link/swap: a 1G repeater chain — A, three SiV relays R₁ R₂ R₃, and B, with four small photonic-BSM symbols between adjacent matter qubits and short magenta entanglement arcs. L2 Encoding/bridges: a peach M-O block on A's side (5 GHz → 1350 nm, η < 1%), a blue QFC block on B's side (737 → 1350 nm, η ≈ 5.4%, PPLN pump 1623 nm), and a middle fibre segment carrying telecom photons with a 'time-bin encoding (Knaut 2024)' note. L1 Physical: a dilution-fridge box on A's side, a diamond-chip box on B's side, and a telecom fibre line carrying photon dots between them, annotated 'Knaut 35 km deployed Boston-metro, 17 dB loss, SNSPDs at receivers'. Footer cites Knaut Nature 629.573 (2024) and Awschalom PRX Quantum 2.017002 (2021)." />
          <figcaption>
            <strong>Q1 stack, layer by layer.</strong> The stack reads top-down:
            the user owns L7 (the data qubit |ψ⟩); L6 protects it with QEC at
            the endpoints; L5 is the network service abstraction (a Bell pair
            on request); L4 is distillation if the raw pairs are below
            threshold; L3 is the repeater chain that extends reach past fibre
            loss; L2 is where the heterogeneity bites — M-O transduction on
            A's side (5&nbsp;GHz → 1,350&nbsp;nm, η&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;1%) versus QFC on
            B's side and at every SiV relay (737 → 1,350&nbsp;nm, η&nbsp;≈&nbsp;5.4%,
            PPLN pumped at 1,623&nbsp;nm); L1 is the telecom-O-band fibre
            itself. The asymmetry between A's bridge and B's bridge is the
            point — they sit in the same row but solve different mismatches.
            Wavelengths and the 35&nbsp;km deployed demo from Knaut et&nbsp;al.
            Nature 629.573 (2024).
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>
          Two infrastructure realities to read off this figure. <strong>First</strong>,
          the M-O transducer on Node&nbsp;A is the only component without a deployable
          device today — everything else either ships or works in the lab. The
          IBM&nbsp;×&nbsp;Cisco&nbsp;×&nbsp;Fermilab programme announced
          November&nbsp;2025 names this exact stage as a 10-year build, with
          proof-of-concept targeted by 2030. <strong>Second</strong>, the fibre
          stretch is only loss-budget-realistic for ≤50&nbsp;km in standard
          single-mode fibre or ≤100&nbsp;km in hollow-core fibre; beyond that range
          the figure becomes Q4 (repeaters), with the pBSM midpoint replaced by a
          chain of memory-equipped repeater nodes performing entanglement
          swapping. See the {" "}<a href={url("/swapping")}>swapping</a> page for
          that primitive.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="forward" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Forward references</h2>
        <p>
          Three follow-on subjects pick up the threads:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Memories</strong> — every M-O transducer pairs naturally with a
            microwave-side or optical-side memory that buffers the conversion event
            against the link's heralding latency. Memory wavelengths and bandwidths
            constrain which transducer technologies pair with which.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>memories</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Links</strong> — the C-band fibre window, the O-band sub-window
            (which Knaut et al. use), and free-space / satellite alternatives all sit
            downstream of QFC. The choice of telecom band shapes which QFC pump and
            which transducer output wavelength the link engineers prefer.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>links</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Distribution</strong> — heterogeneous links between different qubit
            platforms (a superconducting node entangled with an ion-trap node) push the
            work from "one transducer" to "transduction at every interface". Whether a
            quantum internet can be built across platforms with different transition
            frequencies is, in practice, a question answered by the transduction
            technologies on this page.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>distribution</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
